ange, yellow, green, blue, and purple. To the upper left, a black speech bubble displays “$199” in large white text. To the lower right, black text reads “SAMSUNG Galaxy A51.” The phone tilts and rotates slightly, briefly turning sideways while the colorful bars remain visible on its screen.\n\nNext, the plan offer appears as large speech-bubble graphics. A white bubble on the left reads “$45/mo” with “NO CONTRACT” underneath. A larger black bubble on the right reads “UNLIMITED” in bold white letters, with “TALK, TEXT AND DATA” below and smaller text reading “25GB OF HIGH-SPEED DATA, THEN 2G*.” Tiny fine print appears along the bottom, including a note to see terms and conditions at StraightTalk.com.\n\nA red silhouette map of the United States then fills the center-right of the screen. Inside it, white capital letters read “LARGEST, MOST DEPENDABLE NETWORKS*.” The green sky and white clouds continue in the background. More fine print stretches along the bottom in very small black text, giving details about actual availability, coverage, speed, and comparison claims.\n\nThe red map disappears, replaced by bold black text across the center: “TUNE OUT THE NONSENSE.” The same small legal text remains along the bottom while clouds sit around the words.\n\nThe bearded man from earlier returns, now shown full body on a long green dollar-bill road that narrows into the distance. He wears the light blue jacket, pale yellow shirt, olive pants cuffed at the ankles, white socks, and brown shoes. He stands with a loose, rhythmic posture, gesturing with both hands as if dancing or pointing along with what he is listening to. The green money path stretches beneath him, and the white clouds sit low on the horizon behind him.\n\nThe commercial ends on the Straight Talk Wireless logo again, centered over the lime-green sky with white clouds. In the lower right, small white text reads “Available at Walmart” with the Walmart spark symbol. Finally, bold black text appears to the right 